# next-intl Project Rules

## Locales and routing

- Supported locales: `en` (default), `he`
- All user-facing routes live under `/[locale]/` (e.g. `/en`, `/he`)
- Root `/` redirects via `next-intl` middleware — do not add pages outside the locale segment
- Routing config: `src/i18n/routing.ts` using `defineRouting` and `createNavigation`
- Middleware: `src/middleware.ts` with matcher `['/', '/(he|en)/:path*']`
- Use navigation helpers from `@/i18n/routing` (`Link`, `redirect`, `useRouter`, `usePathname`) — not raw Next.js navigation for locale-aware links

## Translations

- Message files: `messages/en.json`, `messages/he.json`
- Server components: `getTranslations({ locale, namespace })` from `next-intl/server`
- Client components: `useTranslations(namespace)` from `next-intl`
- Never hardcode user-visible strings in components — add keys to both locale files
- Keep namespace structure consistent across `en` and `he` (same keys in both files)
- Metadata: use `generateMetadata` with `getTranslations` for localized title/description

## Async params (Next.js 15)

- Route `params` and `searchParams` are Promises — always `await params` before destructuring
- Example: `const { locale } = await params`

## RTL (Hebrew)

- Set document direction in root layout: `dir={locale === "he" ? "rtl" : "ltr"}`
- Set `lang={locale}` on `<html>`
- Prefer logical CSS / Tailwind logical properties over physical left/right:
  - Use `ms-*` / `me-*` instead of `ml-*` / `mr-*`
  - Use `ps-*` / `pe-*` instead of `pl-*` / `pr-*`
  - Use `start` / `end` instead of `left` / `right` where possible
- Font: Rubik with `latin` and `hebrew` subsets (see `src/app/[locale]/layout.tsx`)
- Test both `/en` and `/he` after UI changes — layout mirroring and text alignment must work in both directions

## Locale validation

- Validate `locale` against `routing.locales` in layouts/pages; call `notFound()` for invalid locales
